Colored Scatterplot Matrix¶

Select a categorical attribute and encode its values with color in the scatterplot matrix (e.g. with altair again or seaborn pairplot).

In [76]:
# Plot the selected attributes again and color code the points by position
alt.Chart(df_data).mark_point().encode(
    x='weight_kg',
    y='speed',
    tooltip=['name','hp','defense','type1'],
    color='type1'
).interactive()
#What do you mean "by position"?
Out[76]:

Interpretation¶

My insights are that

  1. most pokemon are very light, and there are a few outliers that are extremely heavy.
  2. the weight does not really correlate to the speed a lot. The fastest are very light, but the heavies are not necessarily slow.

Task: Heat Map

Select suitable attributes and visualise the data in a heatmap, e.g. with seaborn or altair.
Do not create a correlation heatmap. Correlations can already be read from the scatterplot matrix.

In [77]:
# TODO
#source: https://altair-viz.github.io/gallery/simple_heatmap.html
#not a correlation heatmap... what else could there be... a "frequency heatmap"?
#I want to show the amount of type1 and type2 that go together. e.g. if type1=grass && type2=poison is a common matchup
alt.Chart(df_data).mark_rect().encode(
    x='type1',
    y='type2',
    color='count()'
)
Out[77]:

Interpretation¶

My top 2 insights are:

  1. water and ice pokemon often have no type2
  2. many combinations do not exist at all, e.g. bug and dark, or dragon, or electric or fary etc. Bug only has combinations with poison, rock or water.

Task: Parallel Coordinates

Select a categorical attribute and encode the lines with color in the parallel coordinates chart. (e.g. with pandas or altair).

In [79]:
# TODO
#source: https://altair-viz.github.io/gallery/parallel_coordinates.html
#q: quantitative, n:nominal/unordered categorical, o:ordered categorical, t:time
alt.Chart(df_data).transform_window(
    index='count()'
).transform_fold(
    ['hp', 'defense', 'weight_kg', 'speed', 'height_m']
).mark_line().encode(
    x='key:N',
    y='value:Q',
    color='type1:N',
    detail='index:N',
    opacity=alt.value(0.5)
).transform_filter(
    (alt.datum.type1 == 'water') | (alt.datum.type1 == 'fire') | (alt.datum.type1 == 'rock') | (alt.datum.type1 == 'steel')
).properties(width=600,height=400)
Out[79]:

Interpretation¶

My top 2 insights are:

  1. steel scores highes in defense as well as in weight, which finally makes some sense
  2. water is very mixed, but the two outliers with hightes hp are water.
